Food for thought:
The original Nintendo Entertainment System & SNES displayed graphics by referring to a number table (a 2D Array in Java). Each index in the table contained a number, which corresponded to a graphic tile stored in ROM. The CPU would read the table, then "draw" the screen using a sequence of tiles based on the values in the table. The mind boggling part is that the NES & SNES ran at 60 FPS; so each second, the CPU had read the table 60 times and outputted information to the screen.

The NES screen consisted of 256 unique tiles, so for every second of gameplay, the CPU has processed 15,360 tiles!

Electrical engineer here. Got in software engineering because hardware design took too long to get boards fabricated. I cut my teeth on BASIC when the Apple II computer first came out. Had taken a class in FORTRAN in college but that was when you entered the program line-by-line on punch cards. The Apple made it so much easier to program. I remember the first program I wrote was to use Gaussian elimination to solve simultaneous equations. I needed that program for circuit design which involves solving them using Kirchoff's laws. What a feeling it was to see those simultaneous equations being solved nearly instantaneously on the screen!

Nowadays, the software development has, in many ways, gotten far more complex, especially in embedding systems. With real-time operating systems, so much of it is non-deterministic, which makes it really hard to debug, especially with multiple cores running. You also have to depend on third party software which may or may not be bug-free, full developed, or documented. Far more challenging and frustrating than in the early days.

I would just like to mention a few caveats to focusing on computer science in school. Computer science or programming all by itself is a little tastless. Like oatmeal with no cinnamon or fruit to make it interesting. I would recommend you study something else as your major/masters/PhD, and take just enough programming to squeak by. All you need is a basic understanding of how programming languages work, once you have that you can look up the details for whatever you need to program online as you go.

The only good reason to study pure computer science is to actually write programming languages, compilers, operating systems and dig deep into the ideas that make it all work. In almost every other case, you will want to be very knowledgable in whatever field the program you are writing is going to be used in. Be it Physics, Chemistry, Healthcare, Biology, Business, Finance, Social media, Engineering, Design, Architecture, etc... you will want to understand the goal of the program more than the actual programming of it.

Also, be prepared to spend most of your time as a programmer trying to explain things to others, and trying to figure out what the heck someone else was trying to do before they rage quit and left a pile of half cooked sphagetti for someone else to unravel and finish.

With all that said, I really think basic programming skills should be taught in high school or sooner. the same way we are taught to read and write, add and subtract. As it is more and more becoming neccesary to pursue advanced studies in other fields. I find the basic understanding of programming languages WAY more useful than calculus, for example :)
